716647f-a.text:
74 to 48 Bedford Street, east side, south from Commerce to and including Seventh Ave. (Extension), showing in the foreground four 3-story frame houses with brick fronts (Nos. 70 to 64). The 6-story apartment house (No. 62-60) shown is at, what was formerly the N.E. corner of Morton Street (prior to the extension of Seventh Ave.). Building on the extreme right (bearing bank sign) is No. 48 and adjoining the N.E. corner of Leroy Street; Bedford Street at that point being only 37 feet long between Seventh Ave.
and Leroy Street.
May 20, 193S..
P. L. Sperr.

Bedford Street, southwest side, from Commerce Street to the eastern part of Morton Street (originally Ardens Street). This is a very gO0d view of the old frame house at 77 Bedford Street, on the S.W. corner of Commerce Street. Adjoining it is 75 1/2 Bedford Street, the narrowest house in New York, barely ten feet wide, and supposed to be over a hundred years old. It is usually entered around the
corner through the gate on Commerce Street.
1932.

28 to 16 Commerce Street, south side, east from Bedford Street to Seventh Ave. Extension, showing two units of frame houses with briok fronts separated by a remodelled factory building, No. 22-20. They are Nos. 28 to 24 (foreground) and 18 to 16. The apartment shown on the extreme right is at the S.E. corner of Commerce and Bedford Streets;
bearing No. 74-72 on the latter.
September 1937.
George D. Chinn.

716643f-a.text:
Bedford Street, at and adjoining the S. E. corner of Commerce Street, as viewed through fhe courtyard to the rear of same, and on towards the gate leading onto the latter thoroughfare. The stuccoed building on the right and the frame corner house sandwich Miss Edna St. Vincent Miilay's home. This is reputed to be the smallest dwelling (9.6 feet in width) in New York City.
1938-9
Alexander Alland
This photo is one of a series that appeared in the published volume "Portrait of N. Y." by Felix Reisenberg and Alex. Alland, IRGV.
